 DHS Purchases 21.6 Million More Rounds of Ammunition

Federal agency has now acquired enough bullets to wage 30 year war

 February 7, 2013

The Department of Homeland Security is set to purchase a further 21.6 million rounds of ammunition to add to the 1.6 billion bullets it has already obtained over the course of the last 10 months alone, figures which have stoked concerns that the federal agency is preparing for civil unrest.

A solicitation posted yesterday on the Fed Bid website details how the bullets are required for the DHS Federal Law Enforcement Training Center in Artesia, New Mexico.

The solicitation asks for 10 million pistol cartridge .40 caliber 165 Grain, jacketed Hollow point bullets (100 quantities of 100,000 rounds) and 10 million 9mm 115 grain jacketed hollow point bullets (100 quantities of 100,000 rounds).

The document also lists a requirement for 1.6 million pistol cartridge 9mm ball bullets (40 quantities of 40,000 rounds).

An approximation of how many rounds of ammunition the DHS has now secured over the last 10 months stands at around 1.625 billion. In March 2012, ATK announced that they had agreed to provide the DHS with a maximum of 450 million bullets over four years, a story that prompted questions about why the feds were buying ammunition in such large quantities. In September last year, the federal agency purchased a further 200 million bullets.

To put that in perspective, during the height of active battle operations in Iraq, US soldiers used 5.5 million rounds of ammunition a month. Extrapolating the figures, the DHS has purchased enough bullets over the last 10 months to wage a full scale war for almost 30 years.

Such massive quantities of ammo purchases have stoked fears that the agency is preparing for some kind of domestic unrest. In 2011, Department of Homeland Security chief Janet Napolitano directed Immigration and Customs Enforcement to prepare for a mass influx of immigrants into the United States, calling for the plan to deal with the “shelter” and “processing” of large numbers of people.

The federal agency’s primary concern is now centered around thwarting “homegrown terrorism,” but information produced and used by the DHS to train its personnel routinely equates conservative political ideology with domestic extremism.

A study funded by the Department of Homeland Security that was leaked last year characterizes Americans who are “suspicious of centralized federal authority,” and “reverent of individual liberty” as “extreme right-wing” terrorists.

In August 2012, the DHS censored information relating to the amount of bullets purchased by the federal agency on behalf of Immigration & Customs Enforcement, citing an “unusual and compelling urgency” to acquire the bullets, noting that there is a shortage of bullets which is threatening a situation that could cause “substantial safety issues for the government” should law enforcement officials not be adequately armed.

As we highlighted last month, the DHS’ previous ammunition solicitation was awarded to Evian Group, an organization that was formed just five days before the announcement of the solicitation and appeared to be little more than a front organization since it didn’t have a genuine physical address, a website, or even a phone number.

While Americans are being browbeaten with rhetoric about the necessity to give up semi-automatic firearms in the name of preventing school shootings, the federal government is arming itself to the teeth with both ammunition and guns. Last September, the DHS purchased no less than 7,000 fully automatic assault rifles, labeling them “Personal Defense Weapons.”

title: For Sale:  Daniel Defense AR-15 DDM4v7 A3 Flat-Top Upper Assembly 5.56x45mm NATO
postcontent:
The Daniel Defense DDM4v7 Complete AR-15 Upper Assembly features a premium, Cold Hammer Forged Barrel made from Mil-Spec 4150 Chrome-Moly Vanadium Steel that is Chrome Lined for durability and corrosion resistance. M4 feed ramps are incorporated into the barrel extension and upper to enhance reliable feeding, while a true 5.56x45 NATO chamber ensures that both commercial and higher pressure surplus mil-spec ammunition may be safely used. The bolt and carrier both pass a thorough Magnetic Particle Inspection (MPI) test for guaranteed structural integrity, and the gas key is properly staked to its mil-spec bolt carrier. All steel parts feature a heavy Mil-Spec Phosphate finish for superior corrosion resistance and durability, while aluminum parts are Type III Hard Coat Anodized. 

The DDM4v7 comes equipped with the new Daniel Defense MFR 12.0 Modular Rail Handguard system for adding tactical accessories while also free floating the barrel for increased accuracy potential. With the exception of a full length, uninterrupted top rail surface that accommodates virtually any desired sighting arrangement, the MFR's body is a small diameter modular tube that will accept add-on rail sections only where the shooter needs them for accessories. This allows the handguard to remain snag-free, uncluttered and devoid of unused rail space, making for a more comfortable off-hand point of contact than full-length quad rail designs. The 12" handguard covers a pinned, low profile gas block at the Mid-Length gas port position, offering the dual benefits of a longer sight radius and increased gas dwell time for a softer recoil impulse upon firing. This DDM4v7 upper comes complete and ready to shoot with a charging handle assembly, Daniel Defense Flash Hider, and 3 Modular Picatinny Rail Sections.

title: For Sale/Trade:  FI MODEL D Former Colt Pony Star Iver Johnson mini 1911 380
location: Fort Thomas, KY near Cincinnati, Cincinnati, Ohio
postcontent: This would require an FFL transfer to any Ohio or other non-KY buyer.  I would ship.  An FI MODEL D, Cal .380, also known as a Colt Pony (Armslist does not have a category for FI [Firearms International]), with TWO (2) magazines, one original, one NOS aftermarket. Made in Washington, DC, these mini 1911 s had an interesting history but this web site gives the background better than I can explain: http://www.star-firearms.com/firearms/guns/d/index.shtml. Made by or for Colt, Star, Iver Johnson and FI. Locked breach, adjustable rear sight, all steel consruction. Serial number CPA 023*** (Colt Pony Automatic = CPA). In the middle 1970s, Colt decided to offer a .380 auto, and chose to partner with Star. The gun (to be called the Pony) was to be assembled in the US, presumably by Colt, from a Star DK slide & associated internals, with a U.S. made frame. A fixed lanyard loop was added to increase height of the gun and the adjustable sights are typical of features added to get points for the 1968 Gun Control Act, which placed restrictions on importation of small handguns. Safety cams hammer off sear for extra protection. Mechanical condition is excellent, pictures tell the story. No operational issues, and everything works as it should. I have shot, cleaned, and lubed it, so it's tested and ready.

At the last Jackson GunShow I bought a case of 5 one thousand count small rifle primers, I payed a stupid amount for these primers, with tax it was just shy of $30 a 1K primers.
I read the Firearms Industry Reports yesterday, guys its not looking good and their meeting in Texas indicated that Americans are not collecting firearms, they are preparing for war.
In that report, reloading components are not a priority, primers, powder and bullets are going to ammunition, ammunition to military, then law enforcement and what is left to the civilian market.
S&W is producing only 300 handguns a day, the M&P line only, no revolvers or rifles.
Remington, Armalite at capacity, FNH will be at 100% in March, Ruger is @ 75% capacity moving to 100%, MagPul is 1,000,000 mags behind, Federal is producing a Billion rounds a week but mostly for military and government contracts, probably 9 months before it reaches the civilian market. Springfield Armory is maintaining, people are hoarding those rifles to get the market artificially up more than likely.
That said, I have some primers, I will sell no more than 2.5 cartons (2500 primers) at my cost, I will not sell them to the same person. I am going to do my part to make sure at least a few of folks have primers. So I will sale a box of 100 for $3.50. That will cover the cost of the primers and me going to the show.
